## Summary

This work proposes a timing-resolved test of whether prior state-transition history — varied in depth — leaves a measurable residual signature after a system enters a stable repeated state.

By isolating the stabilised phase and enforcing strict control of system-induced scaling, the experiment probes whether standard state-based descriptions fully capture system behaviour.

---

## Plain English Summary

We compare two systems that end up in the same stable state:
* One got there directly
* One got there after lots of flipping

Then we measure only after they stabilise. Quantum mechanics says they should behave the same.

This experiment checks whether:

> After many transitions, a tiny timing effect remains that hasn’t been measured before — and whether it grows with how much history came before.

